268. Croesum . . . vitre .· Croesus was the last king of Lydia and proverbially rich. He asked Solon, the Athenian lawgiver, who was the happiest man Ρ The philosopher told him, ‘⁶ no man could be called happy before death.'’ This afterwards Croesus found to -be true; for being taken by Cyrus and ordered to be burned, he cried out, “ Solon ! Solon! Solon !” Cyrus asked the reason of this and was told what Solon had remarked : whereupon, con- sidering, it might be his own case, he spared his life and treated him with much respect.

Being conquered by Sylla, he fled to the marshes of „Mintur-nce, a town of old Latium, where he was taken and thrown into prison: but, escaping thence into Africa, he was obliged to beg his bread through the streets of Carthage. Campania is there- fore called provida, because, if the fever had killed Pompey, it would have provided against all his after missortuneS, and the dire consequences of a civil war.
